There are a couple points missing from this discussion.

You always have issues about whether you would be better off waiting,
trying the same server over, or trying different servers, etc.  The
optimization is far from simple once you start trading off the cost of
packets on the local net, packets off the local net, the cost of
server calculations, and the cost for tardy answers.  It gets worse
when you start figuring the cost of lines of code in the resolver, and
startegies that locally optimize vs ones that globally optimize
resource use.

VMTP will win for some, but not all scenarios.

Where might VMTP lose in a common scenario?  VMTP serializes the
request/response stream.  This can cause problems in that one request
can be effectively blocked behind another.

paul

